body:
@sergey-vlasov  Can you `TL;DR` the mistake?

@KLINGTdotNET points like yours are exactly the reasons why symlinks were never supported. 
I don't think we can implement a scenario where is everybody is happy, see the discussions in the linked post. (unless your point refers to something @sergey-vlasov has said oppose to the implementation details).

We've concluded on what we can do that makes our life easy by just looking at symlinks as files with some content (content being the target it points to), and if the target doesn't exist or doesn't translate locally, we don't care.

@hobarrera 

> It should not analyze them and alter them based on arbitrary conditions. 

I never said that it should make some "arbitrary" changes. Maybe there are use cases where you don't want to have two copies a large folder tree instead of a symlink. But I admit that copying the plain symlink is what most users seems to expect.
